msgid "ravs"
msgstr "ravs"

#: ../../R/ravs.rst:7
msgid "/ravz/, Chinese ravs, n\\."
msgstr "/ravz/, Chinese ravs, 名詞"

#: ../../R/ravs.rst:9
msgid ""
"[primarily MIT/Boston usage] Jiao-zi (steamed or boiled) or Guo-tie (pan-"
"fried). A Chinese appetizer, known variously in the plural as dumplings, pot"
" stickers (the literal translation of guo-tie), and (around Boston) ‘Peking "
"Ravioli’. The term rav is short for ‘ravioli’, and among hackers always "
"means the Chinese kind rather than the Italian kind. Both consist of a "
"filling in a pasta shell, but the Chinese kind includes no cheese, uses a "
"thinner pasta, has a pork-vegetable filling (good ones include Chinese "
"chives), and is cooked differently, either by steaming or frying. A rav or "
"dumpling can be cooked any way, but a potsticker is always the pan-fried "
"kind (so called because it sticks to the frying pot and has to be scraped "
"off). \"Let's get hot-and-sour soup and three orders of ravs.\" See also "
":ref:`oriental-food`\\."
msgstr ""
"[主にMIT/ボストンの用法] Jiao-zi(蒸しまたはゆで)あるいはGuo-tie(焼き)。中国の前菜で、複数形ではdumplings、pot "
"stickers(guo-tieの直訳)、そして(ボストンあたりでは)‘Peking "
"Ravioli’などさまざまに知られる。ravという語は‘ravioli’の短縮形で、ハッカーの間では常にイタリア式ではなく中国式のものを意味する。どちらもパスタの皮に包まれた具からなるが、中国式はチーズを含まず、より薄いパスタを使い、豚肉と野菜の具(良いものには中国ニラが入る)を持ち、蒸すか焼くかで異なるように調理される。ravやdumplingはどんなやり方でも調理できるが、potstickerは常に焼いたもの(焼き鍋にくっつき、こそげ落とさなければならないのでそう呼ばれる)である。「サンラータンと、ravsを三人前頼もう」。\\"
" :ref:`oriental-food`\\ も参照。"
